        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Video SEO</strong> is the process of optimising video content — titles, descriptions, transcripts, structured data markup, and hosting configuration — so that search engines can discover, index, and rank the video in both Google's universal results and YouTube's internal search engine. It combines traditional on-page SEO principles with platform-specific ranking factors unique to video content, particularly watch time and engagement velocity.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">SEO / Video Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">YouTube SEO, Video Search Optimisation</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">8 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Video is the fastest-growing source of organic search traffic. Google now displays video carousels and rich results for over 26% of search queries. On YouTube — the world's second largest search engine — over 500 hours of video are uploaded every minute. Without active optimisation, your video is invisible to both engines regardless of how good it is.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is video SEO?</h2>
        <p>Video SEO encompasses two distinct but related disciplines:</p>

        <h3>Google video SEO (universal search)</h3>
        <p>Google can surface videos in multiple ways within its search results: video carousels in universal search, video thumbnails in image search, video rich results (with structured data), and direct video answers in featured snippets. Ranking in these positions requires that Google can crawl, index, and understand your video — which is not automatic for site-hosted video.</p>

        <h3>YouTube SEO (platform search)</h3>
        <p>YouTube is its own search engine with over 3 billion searches per month. Ranking on YouTube depends on a mix of metadata signals (title, description, tags, chapters) and engagement signals (watch time, click-through rate, likes, comments, shares). YouTube's algorithm weights the engagement signals heavily — a video that earns strong watch time will be promoted in both search and suggested video placements.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">The indexing gap</div>
          <p>Google automatically indexes YouTube videos but does NOT automatically index videos hosted on your own website. Website-hosted videos without VideoObject schema and a video sitemap are essentially invisible to Google's video search. This is the single most common video SEO mistake.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="ranking-factors">Video SEO ranking factors</h2>
        <p>The ranking factors divide clearly between the two surfaces (Google vs YouTube) and between technical and engagement factors.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Factor</th><th>Google Video</th><th>YouTube</th><th>Weight</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Watch time / Audience retention</strong></td>
                <td>Indirect</td>
                <td>Primary</td>
                <td>Very High</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Title keyword relevance</strong></td><td>High</td><td>High</td><td>High</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Description keyword coverage</strong></td><td>High</td><td>High</td><td>High</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>VideoObject schema</strong></td><td>Required</td><td>N/A</td><td>Very High (Google)</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Transcript / closed captions</strong></td><td>High</td><td>Moderate</td><td>High</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Click-through rate (CTR)</strong></td><td>Indirect</td><td>Primary</td><td>High</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Likes, comments, shares</strong></td><td>Indirect</td><td>Moderate</td><td>Moderate</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Thumbnail quality</strong></td><td>Moderate</td><td>High (CTR)</td><td>Moderate-High</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Chapter timestamps</strong></td><td>High (rich results)</td><td>Moderate</td><td>Moderate</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Video sitemap</strong></td><td>Required</td><td>N/A</td><td>Very High (Google)</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="structured-data">VideoObject schema markup</h2>
        <p>For website-hosted video, VideoObject schema is the most impactful single technical optimisation. Without it, Google cannot reliably understand the video's content, duration, or thumbnail, which means it will not surface in video rich results even if the page ranks well.</p>

        <p>The minimum required properties for Google video rich results:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>name</strong> — the video title</li>
          <li><strong>description</strong> — what the video is about (same as page meta description minimum)</li>
          <li><strong>thumbnailUrl</strong> — URL to the video thumbnail image</li>
          <li><strong>uploadDate</strong> — ISO 8601 date the video was published</li>
          <li><strong>contentUrl</strong> or <strong>embedUrl</strong> — where Google can find the video file or player</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Additional properties that unlock enhanced rich results:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>duration</strong> — video length in ISO 8601 format (e.g., PT4M30S for 4 minutes 30 seconds)</li>
          <li><strong>hasPart with Clip</strong> — key moments with timestamps, enabling timeline preview in search results</li>
          <li><strong>interactionStatistic</strong> — view count, which adds a social proof signal</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="youtube-optimisation">YouTube-specific SEO optimisation</h2>
        <p>YouTube SEO is a combination of pre-upload optimisation (title, description, tags, chapters) and post-upload engagement management.</p>

        <h3>Title optimisation</h3>
        <p>The YouTube title is the single highest-impact metadata field. Best practices: front-load the primary keyword, keep titles under 60 characters (to avoid truncation in search), and use natural language rather than keyword stuffing. Titles formatted as questions ("How do you...?") or list promises ("7 ways to...") consistently earn higher click-through rates than statement titles.</p>

        <h3>Description optimisation</h3>
        <p>YouTube's description is read by both the algorithm and viewers. Use the first 150 characters for the primary keyword-rich summary (this is what shows before the "Show more" truncation). Include chapter timestamps, a call to action, and secondary keyword coverage in the full description. Link to related content on your website to drive traffic and session continuity.</p>

        <h3>Chapters and timestamps</h3>
        <p>Adding chapters (formatted as MM:SS Chapter Name in the description, starting at 0:00) enables YouTube's chapter navigation UI and allows Google to surface specific video segments in search results as Key Moments. This significantly improves CTR for informational queries where users want to jump to the relevant section.</p>

        <h3>Tags</h3>
        <p>YouTube tags have declined in importance since 2020, but they still function as a relevance signal for topic clustering. Use 10-15 tags covering: the exact keyword phrase, close variants, the broader topic category, and your brand name. Avoid using competitor brand names as tags — this violates YouTube's policies.</p>

        <h3>Engagement velocity</h3>
        <p>YouTube's algorithm places significant weight on how quickly a video accumulates engagement in the first 24-48 hours after publishing. This is why publishing time matters: post when your existing audience is most active (check YouTube Studio Analytics for your channel's peak hours) to maximise early engagement and trigger algorithmic promotion.</p>

        <h2 id="google-video">Getting video into Google search results</h2>
        <p>For Google to surface your website video in rich results, you need four things:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>A crawlable video player.</strong> The video must be playable from the page and accessible to Googlebot. Block video with JavaScript lazy-loading that prevents crawling, and you lose the indexing signal.</li>
          <li><strong>VideoObject schema.</strong> Implemented in JSON-LD in the page head. Required for video rich results.</li>
          <li><strong>A video sitemap.</strong> A separate XML sitemap listing all video URLs with their metadata, submitted to Google Search Console. This helps Google discover videos that are embedded on pages with little surrounding text context.</li>
          <li><strong>A high-quality thumbnail.</strong> Google uses the thumbnail specified in schema for the rich result. Use a 1280x720 image (16:9) with clear subject matter and no misleading content.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="keyword-research">Video keyword research</h2>
        <p>Video keyword research differs from standard text SEO keyword research in one critical way: not all keywords trigger video results. You need to identify "video intent" keywords — queries where Google actually shows video carousels or rich results in the SERP.</p>
        <p>Keywords most likely to trigger video results: how-to queries, tutorial queries, review queries, product demonstration queries, and exercise or recipe queries. Keywords unlikely to trigger video results: pure navigational queries, highly commercial transactional queries, and news queries (which trigger Google News instead).</p>
        <p>Check SERP features for any keyword before investing in video production. If Google shows no video carousels for the query, a YouTube video will still rank in YouTube search, but the Google traffic opportunity from video rich results is limited.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">Video SEO optimisation checklist</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Research keyword before scripting.</strong> Validate that the query triggers video results in Google and has reasonable search volume on YouTube.</li>
          <li><strong>Include keyword in the video title</strong> as close to the beginning as naturally possible.</li>
          <li><strong>Write a 200+ word description</strong> for YouTube videos — keyword-rich in the first sentence, chapters in the body.</li>
          <li><strong>Add closed captions.</strong> Either auto-generated (review for accuracy) or manually uploaded. Captions give YouTube and Google more text to index against keyword queries.</li>
          <li><strong>Create a custom thumbnail.</strong> Never use YouTube's auto-generated thumbnail for SEO-priority videos. A human face, bold text, and high contrast outperform generic auto-thumbnails.</li>
          <li><strong>Implement VideoObject schema</strong> on every website page embedding or hosting a video.</li>
          <li><strong>Submit a video sitemap</strong> to Google Search Console.</li>
          <li><strong>Embed YouTube videos on relevant pages</strong> of your website — this sends a cross-property signal to Google that the video is relevant to that URL's topic.</li>
          <li><strong>Build backlinks to video pages.</strong> YouTube video URLs and website video pages both benefit from external links pointing to them.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor in Search Console.</strong> Check the "Video" filter under Performance to see which queries your videos appear for and what their CTR is.</li>
        </ol>

